<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-581-958  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 581 958.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Banking  June 1990 v7 n6 p46(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Third-party cash management services assist cost control. (InsideAutomation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Crowell, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>As banks strive to expand their corporate cash managementbusiness, they are faced with a dilemma.andP;  To ensure the most costeffective system, should they utilize internal resources for cashmanagement, or hire a third party? Corporations have becomeincreasingly demanding and are using stricter criteria inevaluating their banks' performance.andP;  Banks, on the other hand,strive toward building close client relationships, offeringquality products and keeping prices low.andP;  While they have usedin-house resources to handle automated cash management services,banks have found that hidden costs have soared.andP;  Initial andongoing investments in hardware and software acquisition andmaintenance have depleted available profit.andP;  Instead, banks arenow discovering that third-party cash management is much moreefficient and profitable.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BankingData ProcessingCash ManagementFinancial ServicesOutsourcing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>